# Changelog

## 0.7.5 (packaged)

- Track upstream [v0.7.5](https://github.com/zeroclaw-labs/zeroclaw/releases/tag/v0.7.5).

## 0.7.3 (packaged)

- Initial Cloudron package: rebase upstream `ghcr.io/zeroclaw-labs/zeroclaw:debian` onto `cloudron/base:5.0.0`.
- Gateway on port 42617, `healthCheckPath` `/health`, persistent `/app/data`.
- Seeded config with `require_pairing = true` for internet exposure.
- **Security:** add Cloudron `proxyAuth` addon in front of the gateway. Upstream's `GET /pair/code` endpoint is public by design (the dashboard auto-fills the code from it), which lets anyone who can reach the URL pair themselves. Putting Cloudron's user-auth wall in front means only logged-in Cloudron users (per `accessRestriction`) can ever load the dashboard.
- **Auth model:** Cloudron proxyAuth is the *sole* auth wall; ZeroClaw's built-in pairing is disabled (`require_pairing = false`). Rationale: stacking proxyAuth in front of ZeroClaw's pairing-token scheme creates an uncoordinated double-auth â€” the SPA's bootstrap XHR (`/api/status`, `/pair/code`) has no Bearer token yet, so Cloudron 302s it to `/login` before ZeroClaw can serve a pair code, and the SPA tries to `JSON.parse` the login HTML. `supportsBearerAuth: true` makes this worse: Cloudron then requires a Bearer on `/api/*` and refuses cookie-only auth there. Dropped `supportsBearerAuth` and disabled pairing â€” single gate, stronger security (no long-lived Bearer tokens, Cloudron-enforced 2FA, per-user audit via `X-Cloudron-UserId`).
- Harden `[gateway]` defaults: `trust_forwarded_headers = true` (safe behind Cloudron's trusted proxy â€” the rate limiter now sees real client IPs).
- Memory backend: `sqlite` (v0.7.3 supports `sqlite | lucid | qdrant | markdown | none` â€” `"postgres"` is NOT recognised and silently falls back to markdown). SQLite `brain.db` lives in `/app/data/workspace/` and is covered by the `localstorage` addon's filesystem backups.
- **Provider template:** seed with a `custom:<URL>` fallback instead of `fallback = "ollama"`. ZeroClaw's `apply_named_model_provider_profile()` unconditionally rewrites `fallback = "ollama" + base_url` to `custom:<URL>` at load time but only carries `base_url`/`api_path` across, dropping `model` â€” which made the runtime fall through to its hardcoded Anthropic default and hit `404 Not Found`/`model not found`. Declaring the fallback directly as `custom:<URL>` pins base_url + model to the same entry and skips the rewrite. The template URL also now ends in `/v1` because `OpenAiCompatibleProvider` appends `/chat/completions`, and Ollama's OpenAI-compat endpoint lives at `/v1/chat/completions`. Trade-off: routes through Ollama's OpenAI-compat shim (`/v1`) instead of native `/api/chat`; vision still works (OpenAI `image_url` parts), and `reasoning` tokens are still surfaced via the `reasoning` field in the compat response.
- **Reinstall required** (adding `proxyAuth` cannot be done on an existing app â€” Cloudron platform constraint).
- Upstream release notes: https://github.com/zeroclaw-labs/zeroclaw/releases/tag/v0.7.3
